<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I used to use this section header all the time=
; it became a running joke around here in the mid-2010s. Back then, when I =
wrote =E2=80=9Cpeople are worried about bond market liquidity,=E2=80=9D it =
was usually about one (or both) of two overlapping concerns:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32274940.264413/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDYtMDMvcGVvc=
GxlLWFyZS13b3JyaWVkLWFib3V0LWJvbmQtbWFya2V0LWxpcXVpZGl0eT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODAy=
MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1=
fdGVybT0yMzA4MDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9=
2dee85a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> Bonds</a> were not <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/32274940.264413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTItMDMvYm9uZC1pbnZlc3RvcnMtYXJlLXdvcnJpZWQtYWJvdXQtYm9=
uZC1tYXJrZXQtbGlxdWlkaXR5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MDIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW=
09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDgwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ=
249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f1745be" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">liquid</a>. In=
 the olden days, the worry went, banks would commit their balance sheets to=
 buy bonds from investors who wanted to sell them, but now banks are risk-a=
verse and heavily regulated and are unwilling to buy bonds, so it is hard f=
or real investors to sell bonds quickly without crashing the market.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bond mutual funds and, particularly, b=
ond=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32274940.=
264413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMt=
MDEvYXJlLWJvbmQtZXRmcy1jcmVhdGluZy1hLWJvbmQtbWFya2V0LWxpcXVpZGl0eS1pbGx1c2l=
vbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODAyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA4MDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d6bd43b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> exchange-traded funds</a>=C2=A0creat=
ed an =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/322=
74940.264413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
AtMDMtMTIvdGhlLWJ1bGwtbWFya2V0LWNhdWdodC1hLXZpcnVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MDIyM19NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIzMDgwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB95a07e9=
d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> illusion of liquidity</a>=E2=80=9D: People could trade in and=
 out of ETFs in milliseconds, giving them very liquid access to bond exposu=
re, but if everyone wanted out of bond ETFs at once then the ETFs would hav=
e to sell their underlying bonds, which are far less liquid, and which woul=
d lead to problems.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I was never all that excited about either of t=
hese worries, but people were really into them for a while, so I mentioned =
them a lot.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a third concern: What if bonds are=C2=
=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>liquid? Because of bond ETFs? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Mich=
ael Tobin <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32274940=
.264413/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vY2FwaXRhbC1tYXJrZXRzL2V0ZnM=
tY3JlYXRlLWxpcXVpZGl0eS10aGF0LWN1dHMtanVuay1ib25kLXlpZWxkcy1iYXJjbGF5cy1zYX=
lz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB84bf5333" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reported last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rise of exchange-traded junk-bond funds ha=
s made trading high-yield debt cheaper, cutting borrowing costs for compani=
es while reducing potential returns for investors.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yields are between half a percentage point and=
 a full percentage point lower than they=E2=80=99d otherwise be, Barclays P=
lc strategists wrote in a note last week. The falling rewards from buying i=
lliquid bonds have encouraged investors to consider higher-yielding assets =
like private credit instead, the report said. =C2=A0=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">About 8% of junk-bond trading volume stemmed f=
rom portfolio trading at the end of 2022, Barclays strategists including=C2=
=A0Jeff Meli=C2=A0wrote. In 2018, that figure was closer to zero.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe use of these tools has resulted i=
n lower aggregate yields,=E2=80=9D Meli said in an interview.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All those old worries about bond market liquid=
ity never really panned out. Instead, bond ETFs made it easier to trade bon=
ds, particularly high-yield bonds that used to be less liquid. For one thin=
g, if you want bond exposure, you can just buy the ETF shares, which are li=
quid and standardized and give a lot of investors most of what they want, m=
aking bond investing safer and more liquid. For another thing, if you have =
a bunch of bonds that you want to sell, now you might be able to=C2=A0find =
a market maker=C2=A0to do a portfolio trade with you, where they will buy t=
he whole lot of your bonds and use them to create more ETF shares; the cost=
 and market impact of doing this trade will be less than the cost of tradin=
g each bond separately. The result is that for a lot of investors, high-yie=
ld bonds provide a nicer trading experience: They are more liquid, so you c=
an sell them quickly and efficiently, so it is less risky to own them, so y=
ou will be more willing to pay a bit more to buy them, so=C2=A0<em>they wil=
l have lower yields</em>. You used to get paid a premium for their illiquid=
ity, but now they are liquid and you don=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is an obvious trade-off: Bonds are nicer=
, so you pay more for them, so you get lower yields. What if you want highe=
r yields, though? What if you=E2=80=99re not so interested in being able to=
 sell bonds easily, and you=E2=80=99re more interested in maximizing yield?=
 Well, =E2=80=9Cthe falling rewards from buying illiquid bonds have encoura=
ged investors to consider higher-yielding assets like private credit instea=
d.=E2=80=9D At FT Alphaville, Robin Wigglesworth <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32274940.264413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2Nv=
bnRlbnQvMTE3MGVmMzgtYTgxYi00M2VhLWIyOGItMDhmN2Q4OTlkY2Vk/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBbe8a18f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">quotes from the Barclays note</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Active managers, such as HY mutual funds, whic=
h must meet daily redemptions and so must trade a lot, have benefited from =
improved ways to manage liquidity. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, a declining liquidity risk =
premium has likely made asset allocators, such as insurers and pension fund=
s, worse off. These buy-and-hold investors do not manage daily liquidity ne=
eds and are far less sensitive to the liquidity of their bond holdings than=
 mutual funds. Hence, investing in the illiquid HY market provides an attra=
ctive, and yet relatively risk-free way, to generate extra returns for thes=
e type of investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the rewards of investing in HY decline, it =
is possible that investors have tilted portfolios towards other asset class=
es offering more attractive investment opportunities =E2=80=94 such as priv=
ate credit. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While the rise of private credit likely has ma=
ny causes, we believe that the combination of the high return hurdles for a=
sset allocators and the lack of viable alternatives has been an important c=
ontributing factor.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">High-yield bonds are now so liquid that they d=
on=E2=80=99t pay enough of an illiquidity premium to be attractive to long-=
term investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/32274940.264413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMjcvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktaXMtb24tZHJ1Z3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEM=
DgwMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXIm=
dXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwODAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBc8b5559c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> made a related point</a> in June. We discussed the st=
ory of how Bill Gross, like, invented bond trading, and how he made a bunch=
 of money by being early and innovative in trading bonds. But also the stor=
y of how over the last half-century bond trading got so good and popular=C2=
=A0that the returns to bond trading have been competed away, and now asset =
allocators who want credit exposure are looking to private credit because i=
t=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>trade, so it pays more:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The big discovery in investment-gr=
ade credit in the 1970s was =E2=80=9Cbonds are liquid and fungible; let=E2=
=80=99s trade them to make more money.=E2=80=9D The big discovery in invest=
ment-grade credit in the 2020s is =E2=80=9Ctrading is overrated; we can mak=
e more money by doing our own structuring and getting paid for illiquidity.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The big (and controversial) discovery in high-=
yield credit in the 2010s was that if you package high-yield bonds into ETF=
s, they will trade more liquidly and become a more attractive product. The =
big discovery in high-yield credit in the 2020s is that if high-yield bonds=
 trade more liquidly and become more attractive, they will=C2=A0<em>pay les=
s</em>, and so you=E2=80=99ll have to go to private credit to get more illi=
quidity and more yield.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Ruble arbitrage</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In its simplest form, =E2=80=9Carbitrage=E2=80=
=9D means buying something at a low price and selling the same thing, simul=
taneously, at a higher price, somewhere else. Buy a share of stock on the N=
ew York Stock Exchange, sell the same share for a penny more on Nasdaq, tha=
t's arbitrage.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a trivial sense a dollar is always worth mo=
re in the US than it is in Europe, and a euro is always worth more in Europ=
e than it is in the US, just because you can buy a sandwich with dollars bu=
t not euros in the US and vice versa. And your bank or credit card company =
will do that arbitrage for you =E2=80=94 selling you euros for dollars in E=
urope or vice versa =E2=80=94=C2=A0and make a little money, though that bus=
iness is efficient and competitive enough that they probably won=E2=80=99t =
make=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But when Russia invaded Ukraine, all of a sudd=
en there was a real arbitrage: Suddenly nobody in the US or most of Europe =
wanted to own rubles, and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I won=E2=80=99t say that nobody in=
 Russia wanted to own dollars or euros, exactly,<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but for patriotic and capital-control reasons there was a lot of =
demand from Russian exporters=C2=A0to exchange their dollars into rubles. S=
o for a while you could buy a dollar for 59 rubles in Moscow and sell a dol=
lar for 61.5 rubles in New York, which is a pretty good trade. The trade wa=
s complicated, though, by the fact that a US or European bank probably woul=
dn=E2=80=99t be welcome to buy dollars in Moscow, for patriotic and capital=
-control and sanctions reasons, while a Russian bank probably wouldn=E2=80=
=99t be welcome to sell dollars in New York, for similar reasons. So who ca=
n=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>the arbitrage?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The answer is=C2=A0Armenian and Kazakh banks, =
of course, with an assist from like=C2=A0Goldman Sachs. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32274940.264413/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMDIvd2FsbC1z=
